# Demonstrates architectural decision records (ADRs) in .ctx files.
# Decisions capture the "why" behind important choices so agents
# and new team members understand constraints and tradeoffs.

version: 1

summary: |
  E-commerce platform backend. Handles product catalog,
  shopping cart, checkout, and payment processing.
  Decisions below reflect key architectural choices made
  during the initial design phase (Q1 2025).

decisions:
  # A fully accepted decision with alternatives considered.
  - id: d001
    title: "Use PostgreSQL as the primary database"
    status: accepted
    date: "2025-01-10"
    rationale: |
      PostgreSQL provides ACID transactions, JSON columns for
      flexible product attributes, and full-text search for the
      catalog. The team has deep PostgreSQL expertise.
    alternatives:
      - name: "MongoDB"
        reason_rejected: |
          Flexible schema is appealing for product data, but we
          need strong transactional guarantees for checkout and
          payments. Cross-collection transactions in MongoDB are
          limited and add complexity.
      - name: "MySQL"
        reason_rejected: |
          Viable option, but PostgreSQL's JSONB support and
          full-text search capabilities better fit our needs
          without requiring additional services.
    verified_at: "a1b2c3d"
    locked: true
    owner: backend

  # A decision about the payment integration approach.
  - id: d002
    title: "Stripe as the sole payment processor"
    status: accepted
    date: "2025-01-15"
    rationale: |
      Stripe's API is well-documented, supports all our target
      markets, and handles PCI compliance. Using a single provider
      simplifies reconciliation and reduces integration surface.
    alternatives:
      - name: "Multi-provider (Stripe + PayPal)"
        reason_rejected: |
          Adds complexity to checkout flow, reconciliation, and
          error handling. PayPal can be added later if needed
          without changing the core architecture.
      - name: "Adyen"
        reason_rejected: |
          Better pricing at high volume but requires more
          integration work. Our current volume does not justify
          the additional engineering cost.
    verified_at: "a1b2c3d"
    locked: true
    owner: payments

  # A proposed decision that is still under discussion.
  - id: d003
    title: "Event sourcing for order lifecycle"
    status: proposed
    date: "2025-02-20"
    rationale: |
      Order state changes (created, paid, shipped, delivered,
      returned) are a natural fit for event sourcing. It provides
      a complete audit trail and enables rebuilding state at any
      point in time.
    alternatives:
      - name: "Traditional CRUD with audit log"
        reason_rejected: |
          Simpler to implement but loses the ability to replay
          events and reconstruct past state. Audit log is
          append-only but disconnected from the domain model.
    verified_at: "e5f6789"
    locked: false

  # A superseded decision -- kept for historical context.
  - id: d004
    title: "REST API for all client communication"
    status: superseded
    date: "2025-01-05"
    rationale: |
      REST was chosen initially for simplicity. Superseded by
      d005 which adds GraphQL for the product catalog while
      keeping REST for checkout and payments.
    alternatives: []
    verified_at: "a1b2c3d"
    locked: false

  # The decision that superseded d004.
  - id: d005
    title: "GraphQL for catalog, REST for checkout"
    status: accepted
    date: "2025-03-01"
    rationale: |
      The product catalog has deeply nested data (variants,
      images, attributes, reviews) that clients need to query
      flexibly. GraphQL reduces over-fetching for the catalog.
      Checkout and payments remain REST for simplicity and
      because their data shapes are fixed.
    alternatives:
      - name: "GraphQL everywhere"
        reason_rejected: |
          Checkout mutations with payment processing do not
          benefit from GraphQL flexibility and add complexity
          to error handling and webhook integration.
    verified_at: "f0a1b2c"
    locked: false

tags: [ecommerce, backend, architecture]
